        "content": {
          "zh-CN": "Given a matrix $\\mathbf{A}$, for any constant scalar $\\sigma$, we define the **_shifted matrix_** is $\\mathbf{A} - \\sigma {\\bf I}$. If $\\lambda$ is an eigenvalue of $\\mathbf{A}$ with eigenvector ${\\bf x}$ then $\\lambda - \\sigma$ is an eigenvalue of the shifted matrix with the same eigenvector. This can be derived by\n\n$ \\begin{aligned} (\\mathbf{A} - \\sigma {\\bf I}) {\\bf x} &= \\mathbf{A} {\\bf x} - \\sigma {\\bf I} {\\bf x} \\\\ &= \\lambda {\\bf x} - \\sigma {\\bf x} \\\\ &= (\\lambda - \\sigma) {\\bf x}. \\end{aligned} $",
          "en": "Given a matrix $$\\mathbf{A}$$, for any constant scalar $$\\sigma$$, we define the **_shifted matrix_** is $$\\mathbf{A} - \\sigma {\\bf I}$$. If $$\\lambda$$ is an eigenvalue of $$\\mathbf{A}$$ with eigenvector $${\\bf x}$$ then $$\\lambda - \\sigma$$ is an eigenvalue of the shifted matrix with the same eigenvector. This can be derived by\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned} (\\mathbf{A} - \\sigma {\\bf I}) {\\bf x} &= \\mathbf{A} {\\bf x} - \\sigma {\\bf I} {\\bf x} \\\\ &= \\lambda {\\bf x} - \\sigma {\\bf x} \\\\ &= (\\lambda - \\sigma) {\\bf x}. \\end{aligned} $$"
        }
