        "content": {
          "zh-CN": "An invertible matrix cannot have an eigenvalue equal to zero. An eigenvalue equal to zero would imply a trivial solution to $\\mathbf{Ax}=\\mathbf{b}$, a nullspace of nonzero dimension, and therefore a non invertible matrix. Furthermore, the eigenvalues of the inverse matrix are equal to the inverse of the eigenvalues of the original matrix:\n\n$ \\mathbf{A} {\\bf x} = \\lambda {\\bf x}\\implies \\\\ \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\mathbf{A} {\\bf x} = \\lambda \\mathbf{A}^{-1} {\\bf x} \\implies \\\\ {\\bf x} = \\lambda \\mathbf{A}^{-1} {\\bf x}\\implies \\\\ \\mathbf{A}^{-1} {\\bf x} = \\frac{1}{\\lambda} {\\bf x}.$",
          "en": "An invertible matrix cannot have an eigenvalue equal to zero. An eigenvalue equal to zero would imply a trivial solution to $$\\mathbf{Ax}=\\mathbf{b}$$, a nullspace of nonzero dimension, and therefore a non invertible matrix. Furthermore, the eigenvalues of the inverse matrix are equal to the inverse of the eigenvalues of the original matrix:\n\n$$ \\mathbf{A} {\\bf x} = \\lambda {\\bf x}\\implies \\\\ \\mathbf{A}^{-1} \\mathbf{A} {\\bf x} = \\lambda \\mathbf{A}^{-1} {\\bf x} \\implies \\\\ {\\bf x} = \\lambda \\mathbf{A}^{-1} {\\bf x}\\implies \\\\ \\mathbf{A}^{-1} {\\bf x} = \\frac{1}{\\lambda} {\\bf x}.$$"
        }
